{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Provision AWS-hosted Gerrit + rebar MCP; lock rebar's GitHub `main` to Gerrit\n\n## Context\nWe are adopting Gerrit as the gatekeeper for all code merged to rebar's `main`, self-hosted on AWS alongside the rebar MCP server, with GitHub as a downstream read-only mirror (the Go-project topology). This epic stands up that environment and locks the rebar GitHub repo so `main` only advances via commits Gerrit replicates after its submit requirements pass. It is the prerequisite that enables dogfooding the agentic code-review capability on rebar itself.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- A single AWS instance hosts Gerrit (NoteDb, no external DB) + the rebar MCP server.\n- rebar's GitHub `main` can only be updated by Gerrit's replication identity; all other pushes / PR-merges / force-pushes are rejected.\n- An `LLM-Review` label + submit requirement are wired to the rebar MCP server, and a change flows end-to-end (push to Gerrit -> review -> submit -> replicate to GitHub).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] AWS instance (~8 GB; e.g. t4g.large) provisioned; Gerrit + rebar MCP each containerized; Gerrit heap pinned (~2 GB); reverse proxy on 443; Gerrit HTTP 8080 + SSH 29418.\n- [ ] Gerrit rebar project configured: `change.submitWholeTopic=true`; custom `LLM-Review` label; submit requirement = the SINGLE deterministic vote `label:LLM-Review=MAX AND -has:unresolved` (the LLM-Review label is voted by the deterministic pass-3 blocker based on thresholds; there is exactly ONE code-review vote, with no separate human Code-Review or CI Verified votes); `copyCondition` carrying the vote across trivial rebases.\n- [ ] Gerrit replication plugin pushes `main` -> GitHub (non-force), authenticated by a dedicated single-repo write **deploy key** as the replication identity (see S5). (Supersedes the earlier 'GitHub App / service account' phrasing: a deploy key is the simpler fit for one repo, and is the sole ruleset bypass actor in S6.)\n- [ ] GitHub rebar repo locked: ruleset restricts `main` updates to the replication identity only (block force-push + deletions); repo write limited to that identity; no human/admin bypass.\n- [ ] rebar MCP server reachable by Gerrit (stream-events/webhook) and can vote `LLM-Review` via REST.\n- [ ] End-to-end proof: a test change is reviewed + submitted in Gerrit and appears on GitHub `main`; a direct GitHub push / PR-merge to `main` is rejected.\n\n\n## Decomposition & resolved design questions (2026-06-28 brainstorm + derisk + peer review)\nDecomposed into **9 stories**: S1 (TF base), S2 (Gerrit + review-bot receiver + nginx/TLS), S3\n(project/label/submit-req/topic), S4a (bot identity + event plumbing), S4b (receiver review/vote\nlogic + backfill), S5 (replication), S6-pre (mirror-lock pre-work), S6 (apply mirror lock), S7\n(e2e + backup/restore + monitoring). The plan-review gaps on the original ACs are resolved as:\n- **IaC tooling + remote state:** Terraform with an S3 backend (`use_lockfile`, TF >= 1.10) + a\n  one-time state-bucket bootstrap — S1.\n- **Secrets management:** AWS SSM Parameter Store SecureString + a least-privilege instance-role\n  policy, pulled to a `chmod 600` `.env` at boot — S1/S2 (scoping reinforced in S4a).\n- **rebar MCP is stdio-only -> Gerrit can't reach it:** S2 stands up a thin **webhook->review->vote\n  RECEIVER** (a plain HTTP service that IMPORTS the review kernel as a library) behind nginx at\n  `/review/`; the stdio MCP is NOT exposed over HTTP (Gerrit POSTs webhooks, not MCP — an MCP HTTP\n  transport would reject the webhook). S4a wires the bot identity/plugins/inbound auth; S4b the\n  review/vote logic.\n- **Gerrit event mechanism:** the `webhooks` plugin (push) + the `events-log` plugin with a\n  reconciler poller for backfill — S4a/S4b. (Not SSH stream-events.) NOTE: the `webhooks` plugin\n  has NO native HMAC, so inbound auth is a secret-token URL + network ACL (S4a), not a signature.\n- **NoteDb persistence + backup:** NoteDb on a dedicated gp3 EBS volume at `/var/gerrit` with\n  `prevent_destroy` + DLM daily snapshots (S1) and a non-destructive restore drill (S7); merged\n  code is always safe on the GitHub mirror.\n- **gate verdict -> `LLM-Review` integer mapping:** the gate's `finalize_verdict` emits\n  `PASS`/`BLOCK`/`INDETERMINATE`; the voter maps `PASS`=+MAX, `BLOCK`/`INDETERMINATE`=-1\n  (fail-closed), config-driven — S4b.\n\n**AC4 refinement:** the lockdown is a REPO-LEVEL ruleset (navapbc is a `free` org; admin-proof\norg-level rulesets need a paid plan). So \"no human/admin bypass\" means no direct/accidental\npushes + force-push/deletion blocked (proven empirically: an active deploy-key-only ruleset\nrejects an admin push); TRUSTED repo admins can deliberately edit/disable the rule — an\nexplicitly accepted PoC risk. The existing `main-protection` ruleset (PR + status-checks) is\nreplaced by the mirror lock (S6).\n\n**Peer-review corrections (folded into the children):** (a) S6 uses `terraform-provider-github`\n>= 6.8.0's NATIVE DeployKey bypass (the prior `null_resource`/`gh api`/two-phase dance is\ndropped); `actor_id:null` is canonical (empirically confirmed). (b) S4 split into S4a/S4b and\nreframed to a webhook receiver (not MCP-over-HTTP); inbound auth via secret-URL + ACL (the\nplugin has no HMAC); async ACK + idempotency vs `webhooks` retries. (c) S3 copyCondition is\n`changekind:NO_CODE_CHANGE` only (dropping `TRIVIAL_REBASE`, which would certify a moved-base\ntree). (d) S5 adds a `projects=` single-repo binding (a functional bug otherwise) + a crash-safe\n`replication.eventsDirectory`.\n\n## Plan-review remediation notes (recalibrated gate)\n- **Rollback / availability (T4):** replacing `main-protection` is reversible — S6 documents a <15-min rollback (ruleset `enforcement=disabled`, restore `main-protection` from the S6-pre snapshot, re-enable PRs/Issues/Actions). Outage posture is the locked **freeze-and-restore** (no break-glass v1): if Gerrit/the receiver/LLM is down, `main` freezes until restored; merged code is always safe on the GitHub mirror.\n- **Architecture decisions captured (T5e):** recorded as ADRs in the children — 0007-review-bot-receiver + 0008-secrets-source-ssm (S2), 0009-review-bot-pipe (S4b), 0010-gerrit-github-replication (S5), 0011-github-mirror-lock (S6-pre), 0012-iac-foundations (S1). CLAUDE.md is updated when d251 lands.\n- **Integration de-risked up-front, not only at S7 (G5):** the two riskiest seams were validated empirically before build (session_log vivid-mull-need): (a) an active repo-level ruleset with deploy-key-only bypass REJECTS a non-bypass admin push (proven on the real repo, GH013); (b) the DeployKey bypass `actor_id:null` is accepted + canonical; (c) Gerrit 3.14.1 boots on arm64 and the submit-requirement predicate + nginx %2F config validate. S7 remains the full e2e proof, but the high-risk mechanisms are already de-risked.\n- **What S4b's \"proven pipe\" actually reviews (G6 seam):** the d251 receiver casts the `LLM-Review` vote by invoking the EXISTING `rebar.llm.review_code(...)` (single-pass, ships today) — clean->label MAX, issues/error->-1 fail-closed — proving the webhook->review->vote->submit->replicate plumbing. The REAL four-pass code-review gate (criteria/prompts/context via `gate_dispatch.produce_code_review_verdict`) is **b744-WS6**, which swaps into the same seam for the dogfood. d251 proves the pipe; b744 supplies the review depth. (Note: this is CODE review — verdict PASS|BLOCK — not the plan-review gate's `finalize_verdict`.)\n\n## Round-7 remediation\n- **Proven-pipe decision rule (G6):** `rebar.llm.review_code()` returns a `review_result` (a `findings` list), NOT a verdict string. The receiver derives a binary decision: **BLOCK if any finding is at/above a configured blocking severity (default critical/high), else PASS** -> PASS->label MAX, BLOCK or error/no-result->-1 (fail-closed); the threshold is config-driven. b744-WS6 swaps in `gate_dispatch.produce_code_review_verdict` (typed `{verdict: PASS|BLOCK}`), removing the derivation."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782711267338774001,"uuid":"6fa5a9ed-8314-4632-8cd2-cfb9b6af1a77"}